  "prompt": "Is it like, illegal to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** is **illegal** in virtually every country, including the United States and most jurisdictions worldwide. Money laundering is the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legitimate by funneling it through legal businesses or financial systems. This is done to conceal the illicit origins of the funds and avoid detection by law enforcement or tax authorities.\n\n### Why is it illegal?\nMoney laundering is a crime because it:\n1. **Facilitates illegal activities** (e.g., drug trafficking, corruption, fraud, terrorism).\n2. **Undermines financial systems** by introducing tainted money into legitimate economies.\n3. **Allows criminals to profit** from their illegal activities without consequences.\n\n### Legal Consequences\nPenalties for money laundering vary by country but can include:\n- **Heavy fines**\n- **Imprisonment** (often ranging from years to decades)\n- **Seizure of assets**\n- **Loss of business licenses or professional standing**\n\nIn the U.S., for example, money laundering is prosecuted under federal laws like the **Bank Secrecy Act** (BSA) and the **Money Laundering Control Act** (MLCA), and offenders can face up to **20 years in prison** per count, depending on the severity of the crime.\n\nIf you suspect someone is involved in money laundering, it\u2019s important to report it to the appropriate authorities.",
